05901nam a22007455i 9781501771583DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017715837 a10.1515/97815017715832doi  a(DE-B1597)666954  a(OCoLC)1370009354  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN345 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.01223/eng/2023021300aBeyond Description :bAnthropologies of Explanation /ced. by Matei Candea, Paolo Heywood. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b1 b&w halftone  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Ethnographies of Explanation and the Explanation of Ethnography -- tPart 1: ON ANTHROPOLOGICAL EXPLANATIONS -- t1. Are There Anthropological Problems? -- t2. On Anthropological Findings -- t3. On (Not) Explaining the Domestic Miracle -- t4. Emergent Explanation -- t5. Bourdieu, the Demystifying Power of Individualism, and the Crisis of Anthropology -- t6. The Economic Explanation -- tPart 2: ETHNOGRAPHIES OF EXPLANATION -- t7. Anthropological Explanation by Virtue of Individual Worldviews and the Case of Stanley Spencer -- t8. Explaining Post-truth -- t9. Finding Real and Fake Explanations -- t10. Explaining Mindfulness in Political Advocacy -- t11. Explaining the Politics of the Author -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aBeyond Description brings anthropologists and other social scientists together to examine the problem of explanation. What is "an explanation?" What can it add? What makes it authoritative, clarifying, or misleading? Whom does it serve and how is it produced? These questions lie at the heart of recent public crises of confidence in expertise, political representation, and classic liberal visions of whom we can rely on for true and trustworthy accounts. In a world beset by events and processes that seem to defy expert predictions of their impossibility, and in which post-hoc accounts can often feel more like rationalizations than explanations, competing voices vie for public presence and seek to silence one another. Anthropology and the social sciences face such questions too, making contemporary explanatory practice both an empirical and a reflexive challenge. By combining ethnographic studies of practices of explanation in a range of contemporary political, medical, artistic, religious, and bureaucratic settings, the essays in Beyond Description offer critical examinations of changing norms and forms of explanation in the world and within anthropology itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnologyxPhilosophy. 0aExplanation. 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 4aEDUCATION & HISTORY OF EDUCATION. 4aSOCIOLOGY & SOCIAL SCIENCE. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  apolitical phenomenon, post-truth, cognitive therapy, empirical questions, ethnographic studies, examinations, anthropology, epistemological questions, philosophy, sociology, epistemology, interpretation, social analysis.1 aBialecki, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandea, Matei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandea, Matei, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarter, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeywood, Paol